{{Infobox non-profit | name = Normandy Youth Club–The N-Factor | logo = | type = [[Non-governmental organization]] | founded_date = 2008 | location = [[Normandy, Surrey|Normandy]], [[Surrey, England|Surrey]], UK | key_people = Maria Angel MBE BA(Hons) PGCE QTLS FCMI | area_served = Surrey | focus = [[Youth programs|Youth]], [[Mentorship]], [[Community cohesion]] | homepage = {{URL|http://www.thenfactor.btck.co.uk/}} }} The '''Normandy Youth Club–The N-Factor''' was founded in the [[United Kingdom]] in July 2008, and launched in January 2009 to help combat the increasing incidents of youth crime in [[Normandy, Surrey|Normandy]], [[Surrey, England|Surrey]] and its surrounding hamlets.
==History== After a gap of not having an area youth club for over two decades Mrs Maria Angel [[MBE]]<ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-year-honours-list-2018-department-for-education.</ref>, BA (Hons) Bus & Mgt, PGCE, QTLS, FCMI, a School and Sixth Form teacher, recognised the lack of out of school hours youth leisure facilities within the parish of [[Normandy, Surrey]].<ref name="Mum"/> She founded the "Normandy Youth Club–The N-Factor" to help combat the increasing incidents of youth crime in the community.<ref name="Mum">[http://img.tesco.com/todayattesco/lifestyle_and_fashion/mum_of_the_year_maria_angel.shtml ''Mum of the Year'']; article at [[Tesco]] Magazine on-line; retrieved January 2013.</ref> The group is based out of Normandy Village Hall<ref> [https://www.brookesalumni.co.uk/page.aspx?pid=728 ''Business alumna awarded Tesco Magazine "Mum of the Year".'']; 30 March 2010 article; Brookes Alumni Magazine on line; accessed 02 November 2013.</ref> and caters specifically to youth aged eight to 18 years of age.<ref>[http://img.tesco.com/todayattesco/lifestyle_and_fashion/mum_of_the_year_maria_angel.shtml "Mum of the Year: Maria Angel".'']; [[Tesco]] Magazine on-line; accessed 02 November 2013.</ref>
==Aims, Objectives & Initiatives== The youth club encourages all children and young people to become more socially included within the rural community of Normandy.<ref name="Mum"/> The organization is a voluntary, rural community youth club that does culturally sensitive youth work and has concentrated its efforts in targeting young people from disadvantaged and marginalised communities in Normandy and its surrounding hamlets, including those from the [[minority group]] communities (such as [[Names of the Romani people#Gypsy and Gipsy|Gypsy]], [[Irish Travellers]] and [[Showman]]).<ref>[http://www.surreyhighsheriff.org/Launch-of-The-N-Factor.asp ''The Surrey High Sheriff Youth Award 2009 and 2010''].</ref> It provides [[NEET|Not in Employment Education or Training]] (NEET) support and [[mentorship]] programmes for volunteer supervisors and members.<ref>[http://www.surreyyouthfocus.org.uk/userfiles/Issue%20No%2053.pdf ''Userfiles'']; Surrey Youth Focus on-line; retrieved January 2013.</ref>
Creative-based youth club programmes have included adopting the [[Equality and Human Rights Commission]] (EHRC) 'Walk a mile in my shoes' initiative, which embraces the principles of the 'Rights to Dignity and Respect'. The Normandy Youth Club–The N-Factor creative art workshops, provide a platform to interpret and express those principles through art, film and photography. Opportunities to showcase the children and young people's talents, have been organised through Summer art and photographic competitions<ref>[http://www.surreycommunity.info/normandypc/village/news-and-views/summer-photographic-competitio/ ''Photo Competition'']; Surrey Community Information; on-line; retrieved January 2013.</ref> thereby positively raising the profile of and engaging its young members with the rest of the community.<ref name="Mum"/><ref>[http://www.surreylife.co.uk/people/charity/surrey_life_community_heroes_2014_who_really_makes_a_difference_to_life_in_your_town_or_village_1_3260292/ ''Surrey Life Community Heroes 2011'']; Great British Life article; retrieved January 2013.</ref>
==Recognition== The Normandy Youth Club–The N-Factor has been recognised for its work towards "[[community cohesion]]," both locally and nationally. The youth club has also received many national community awards and was recognised by the UK Prime Minister Gordon Brown and his wife [[Sarah Jane Brown|Sarah]] in 2010.<ref>[http://resources.cohesioninstitute.org.uk/GoodPractice/Projects/Project/Default.aspx?recordId=334 Good Practice Projects] at cohesion institute; retrieved 10 February 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/s/2053193_local_heroes_honoured_at_police_awards_ceremony/ ''Local Heroes Honored'']; [[Surrey Advertiser]] Get Surrey Group news on-line; retrieved January 2013.</ref><ref name="NYC"> [http://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/local-news/award-mother-who-transformed-village-4817930 ''Award for Mother Who Transformed Her Village'']; 18 October 2010 article; at [[Surrey Advertiser]] Get Surrey Group news on-line; retrieved 30 January 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.guildford.gov.uk/CHttpHandler.ashx?id=10515&p=0 Guilford Government site][[Borough of Guildford]]; retrieved January 2013.</ref>
