In a [[Philippines]] rife with corruption and poverty, [[Contract killing|hitmen]] Mario and Daniel are prisoners who are frequently released and paid to perform hits for their boss, Thelma. Mario spends his earnings on his law school tuition for his daughter Tina, and for his estranged wife, Lulette. Daniel, the younger and most reckless partner, pays remittances to his family and spends the rest on goods and privileges inside prison. Daniel has come to see Mario as a mentor and [[father figure]]. After the pair murder [[drug lord]] Tiu and return to prison, Tiu's murder case is assigned to [[National Bureau of Investigation (Philippines)|NBI]] Agent Francis Coronel through the agent's father-in-law, Congressman Manrique. Coronel's father, also a police officer, died amid rumors of corruption. When Coronel and his partner Bernabe arrive at the local precinct, they clash with [[Philippine National Police|PNP]] Sergeant Joaquin Acosta, a twenty-year veteran who believes the case was taken from him for political reasons.

Mario and Daniel next carry out a hit on a woman named Linda. Upon hearing of her death, Linda's husband, Pol, immediately calls Acosta. Pol reveals that Tiu's murder is one of several assassinations ordered by Manrique's close friend General Pacheco, a military officer campaigning for public office in the [[Senate of the Philippines|Senate]]. Pacheco runs a gun-for-hire operation using prisoners, and kills others involved in the business in order to protect his campaign. Acosta agrees to protect Pol and heads to the station, where he finds Coronel and Bernabe. While the two confront Acosta, Daniel shoots Pol, but his pistol [[Firearm malfunction|jams]] before he can deliver the fatal shot. The three officers converge on them, forcing Daniel and Mario to flee. Daniel shoots a hospital janitor to create a distraction, allowing Mario to kill Pol. The two then split up to escape; Coronel and Bernabe chase Daniel, and Acosta pursues Mario. During the chase, Bernabe is shot, and Mario sprains his ankle.

Coronel confronts Manrique during a campaign meeting, and explains that he intends to arrest Pacheco, but Manrique warns Coronel that Pacheco's indictment will cause their downfall, as Manrique is one of Pacheco's clients. Acosta relays Mario's [[Facial composite|composite sketch]] to the police to be broadcast on television. Frustrated of his father-in-law's involvement with Pacheco, Coronel decides to work with Acosta, who informs him that his father was not corrupt, but was in fact killed while trying to expose corruption{{em dash}}Acosta himself was demoted for his part in working to weed out corruption. When Coronel discovers Mario's identity, he visits Lulette, who is with her lover, Boy. Coronel informs Acosta of Lulette's affair, and he attempts to use it as leverage while interrogating Mario. He is unsuccessful, but Mario later expresses to Daniel a sense of betrayal by his family's abandonment.

Tiu's father tells Acosta and Coronel that he can provide them with the evidence they need to arrest Pacheco. On the way, though, Coronel abandons Acosta to visit Pacheco, who admits that he killed Coronel's father. Coronel secretly records a conversation between Pacheco and his men regarding the murder of Tiu's father.

The next day, Coronel informs his wife Nicky of his intention to take down Pacheco, incriminating Manrique in the process. Daniel murders Coronel in front of police headquarters. Enraged, Acosta attacks Manrique's and Pacheco's security detail, resulting in a brief shootout, until Pacheco orders them to cease fire. On the day Mario is to be released from prison, he realizes that he has no reason to leave, as his family no longer wants to have anything to do with him, and he stabs Daniel to death in order to remain incarcerated. Coronel's death is mourned by many, including Nicky. Acosta is discharged and investigated for Coronel's murder. Mario visits home, kills Boy in front of his family, and returns to prison.

Sometime later, a recovered Bernabe looks through Coronel's possessions and finds the cell phone that Coronel used to secretly record the incriminating conversation between Manrique and Pacheco. Bernabe requisitions the phone as evidence.

== Production ==
=== Development ===
[[File:Erik Matti 10-20-14 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|alt=A photograph of a smiling, heavyset gray-haired man wearing glasses with his tattooed arms crossed. Some bystanders are seen in the background.|Director Erik Matti during the film's premiere at the 2014 [[Morelia International Film Festival]]]]
The director of ''On the Job'', [[Erik Matti]], took inspiration from a [[chauffeur|service driver]] of [[Viva Films]] who claimed to have been temporarily released from prison to perform contract killings before being reincarcerated.<ref name="eastern">{{cite news|last1=Heskins |first1=Andrew |title=Erik Matti: getting the job done |url=http://www.easternkicks.com/features/erik-matti-getting-the-job-done |accessdate=May 24, 2017 |publisher=EasternKicks.com |date=June 4, 2014 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602232942/http://www.easternkicks.com/features/erik-matti-getting-the-job-done |archivedate=June 2, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Matti shelved this idea until he ended his hiatus from directing. In 2009, he submitted a [[short film]] he directed entitled ''The Arrival'' and an eight-minute trailer of ''On the Job'', featuring [[Joel Torre]], to [[film festival]]s in an attempt to [[pitch (filmmaking)|pitch]] the project.<ref name="eastern" /> Both entries were met with critical acclaim,<ref name="esquire">{{cite news|last1=Gomez |first1=Jerome |title=The Long History Behind Erik Matti's Barrier-Breaking ''On The Job'' |url=http://www.esquiremag.ph/culture/arts-and-entertainment/erik-matti-on-the-job-a1549-20170421-lfrm7 |accessdate=May 24, 2017 |work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |location=Philippines |date=August 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170604114102/http://www.esquiremag.ph/culture/arts-and-entertainment/erik-matti-on-the-job-a1549-20170421-lfrm7|archivedate=June 4, 2017 |issn=2243-8459}}</ref> but the trailer piqued the interest of [[Twitch Film]] editor Todd Brown, who inquired if the project had entered production. When Matti told him that the film did not yet have a screenplay, Brown encouraged him to write it while he looked for investors for financing.<ref name="esquire" /> On the script's ninth revision, screenwriter [[Michiko Yamamoto (screenwriter)|Michiko Yamamoto]] came on board to help finalize the remainder of the draft.<ref name="esquire" /> Four uncredited consultants were also hired to develop details in the story.<ref name="Budget" />

During the writing process, and even after the final draft was complete, Brown was unable to attract financiers; some felt the story was too nontraditional for Philippine cinema or too large a risk for overseas market.<ref name=eastern /><ref name="esquire" /> [[Star Cinema]], the largest production company in the Philippines, refused to make the film in 2010, as it was too violent and intense compared to their usual [[romantic comedy]] projects.<ref name="esquire" /><ref name="yang">{{cite news|last1=Yang |first1=Tatin |title=Attamovie!—How ''On The Job'' all-in gamble paid off |url=http://lifestyle.inquirer.net/124059/attamovie-how-on-the-job-all-in-gamble-paid-off/ |accessdate=July 4, 2017 |newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |date=September 7, 2013 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014142039/http://lifestyle.inquirer.net/124059/attamovie-how-on-the-job-all-in-gamble-paid-off |archivedate=October 14, 2013 }}</ref> Matti offered the project to two of Star Cinema's talents, who also declined due to its gore and violence.<ref name="eastern" /><ref name="esquire" /> The project was once again put on hold as Matti entered the [[post-production]] stage of his [[horror fantasy]] film ''[[Tiktik: The Aswang Chronicles]]'' (2012). At this time, he was contacted by an agent of Star Cinema requesting the revised script; three days later, the studio agreed to fund the film.<ref name="esquire" />

[[Reality Entertainment]], an [[independent film]] company Matti co-founded, co-produced ''On the Job'' with Star Cinema. Dondon Monteverde, co-founder of Reality Entertainment, said that many studios were impressed by the script but were reluctant to finance an expensive [[action film]].<ref name="yang" /> The production team considered reducing the film's budget, but decided not to, hoping to shift away from making [[low-budget films]]; Monteverde recalled arguing that it was "really time to do something big-budget and showcase it, rather than making something small and claiming budgetary restrictions. This time we didn't give ourselves any excuses. We went all the way".<ref name="yang" /> The production cost for the film amounted to [[Philippine peso|₱]]47 million<ref name="Budget" /> (about [[United States Dollar|US$]]1.1 million in 2013).{{efn|name=fn1|The exchange rate in 2013 was 42.446 Philippine peso (₱) per 1 US dollar (US$), making ₱47 million worth about US$1.107 million.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Williamson|first1=Samuel H.|title=Exchange Rates Between the United States Dollar and Forty-one Currencies|url=https://www.measuringworth.com/datasets/exchangeglobal/result.php?year_source=2013&year_result=2016&countryE%5B%5D=Philippines|publisher=MeasuringWorth|accessdate=September 7, 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170910220812/https://www.measuringworth.com/datasets/exchangeglobal/result.php?year_source=2013&year_result=2016&countryE%5B%5D=Philippines|archivedate=September 10, 2017|df=}}</ref>}}

=== Pre-production and filming ===
{{Double image|right|alt=Head shots of two men. On the left is Piolo Pascual, wearing a blue polo shirt and smiles before audiences; on the right is Gerald Anderson, wearing a coat with printed shirt underneath and a pendant.|Piolo Pascual at the Star Magic Concert Tour in Ontario, CA, June 2009.jpg|135|Gerald Anderson.jpg|128|[[Piolo Pascual]] (''left'') and [[Gerald Anderson]]}}
Joel Torre, who portrays Mario "Tatang" Maghari in the film, had already been cast before Matti's script revision; [[Angel Aquino]] plays his wife Lulette and [[Empress Schuck]] portrays his daughter Tina.<ref name="prodnotes" /><ref name="rave" /> Of the role, Torre said, "[Mario] stuck with me, fought for me. And that gave me a lot of confidence, a Bushido Blade samurai."<ref name="esquire" /> Matti asked [[Piolo Pascual]] to play the role of Attorney Francis Coronel Jr;<ref name="esquire" /> [[Shaina Magdayao]] plays his wife Nicky and [[Michael de Mesa]] portrays his father-in-law Congressman Manrique.<ref name="prodnotes" /><ref name="rave">{{cite news|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/lifestyle/09/05/13/why-job-getting-rave-reviews|title=Why ''On The Job'' is getting rave reviews|date=September 5, 2013|publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]]|last1=Joaquin|first1=Teodoro Jose|accessdate=May 24, 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161114152122/http://news.abs-cbn.com/lifestyle/09/05/13/why-job-getting-rave-reviews|archivedate=November 14, 2016|df=}}</ref> The role of Daniel was originally written for [[John Lloyd Cruz]], who was interested but had to decline due to scheduling conflicts; it went instead to [[Gerald Anderson]]. After a discussion between Pascual and Anderson about the film, Anderson signed on for the role. Anderson had only two weeks to film his scenes as he was occupied with a [[soap opera]] shoot at the time.<ref name="esquire" /> Dawn Jimenez appeared in her acting debut as Anderson's girlfriend Diane.<ref name="prodnotes" /><ref name="league" />

The role of Sergeant Joaquin Acosta was to be played by [[Richard Gomez]], but he chose instead to pursue a political career in [[Ormoc]].<ref name="esquire" /><ref name="joey">{{cite news|title=How comedian Joey Marquez was cast for ''OTJ'' |url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/08/22/13/how-comedian-joey-marquez-was-cast-otj |accessdate=May 25, 2017 |publisher=ABS-CBN News |date=August 23, 2013 |deadurl=no |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223141725/http://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/08/22/13/how-comedian-joey-marquez-was-cast-otj|archivedate=February 23, 2018}}</ref> Matti later cast [[Joey Marquez]]; although Marquez was seen primarily as a comedian, Matti believed he would be able to portray a simultaneously charismatic and obnoxious character.<ref name="joey" /> The cast also features [[Leo Martinez]] as General Pacheco, [[Lito Pimentel]] as Pol, [[William Martinez (actor)|William Martinez]] as Rex, [[Vivian Velez]] as Thelma, and [[Rayver Cruz]] as Bernabe.<ref name="prodnotes" />
[[File:Red EPIC camera.jpg|thumb|left|250px|alt=A photograph of the Red EPIC camera, with its output screen unfolded.|''On the Job'' was shot with the Red EPIC camera.]]
Richard V. Somes was both the [[production designer]] and [[stage combat|action choreographer]] of ''On the Job''.<ref name="Variety review" /> To prepare for the prison scenes, the production crew built a set in an abandoned building in [[Marikina]], hiring two hundred [[Extra (acting)|extras]] to play convicts.<ref name="esquire" /> [[Principal photography]] lasted thirty-three days, on location in multiple [[Manila]] areas, including [[Manila City Hall]], a [[Manila Light Rail Transit System|Light Rail]] train station, and [[Caloocan]].<ref name="rogue">{{cite news|last1=Jaucian |first1=Don |title=The Game Changer |url=https://roguemagazine.squarespace.com/features/on-the-job |accessdate=May 25, 2017 |work=Rogue Magazine |date=June 16, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170604114102/https://roguemagazine.squarespace.com/features/on-the-job|archivedate=June 4, 2017 }}</ref>  The opening scenes were shot during the annual [[Basaan Festival]] in [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan]].<ref name="pepreview" /> Filming was stretched across over seventy locations,<ref name="esquire" /> and the crew sometimes shot numerous areas in a given day.<ref name="rogue" /> On choosing Manila as a key location for the film, Matti said:

{{blockquote|text=This is a Manila movie. We wanted to show as much of the cross section of Manila as we could. This is, I think, the most ambitious attempt at putting together as much variety [in a local film] in terms of look and feel.<ref name="esquire" />}}

Francis Ricardo Buhay III served as the [[cinematographer]], who had also worked on Matti's films ''Tiktik'' and ''Rigodon'' (2013).<ref name="gmareview" /> Rather than setting up and changing lights for certain shots, Buhay captured the film using the [[Red Digital Cinema Camera Company|Red]] EPIC camera;<ref name="rogue" /> with the Red EPIC's available lighting function, including the ability to light an entire set, the film was styled as a [[neo-noir|modern noir]] without appearing low-budget.<ref name="esquire" />

=== Music ===
Erwin Romulo, the editor-in-chief for the Philippine edition of ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' until 2013, served as the musical director of ''On the Job''.<ref name="erwin">{{cite news|last1=Romulo |first1=Erwin |title=The truth behind ''On the Job'' |url=http://www.philstar.com/young-star/2013/09/06/1175681/truth-behind-job |accessdate=May 26, 2017 |newspaper=The Philippine Star |date=September 6, 2013 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161025150613/http://www.philstar.com/young-star/2013/09/06/1175681/truth-behind-job |archivedate=October 25, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Cruz |first1=Jonty |title=The unedited Erwin Romulo |url=http://www.philstar.com/sunday-life/2015/12/13/1531881/unedited-erwin-romulo |accessdate=May 26, 2017 |newspaper=The Philippine Star |date=December 13, 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160529161243/http://www.philstar.com/sunday-life/2015/12/13/1531881/unedited-erwin-romulo |archivedate=May 29, 2016 |df= }}</ref> At their first meeting, Matti hired Romulo as the [[music supervisor]], but Romulo's role transformed as he wanted to produce most of the tracks he had planned for the film. Romulo employed lesser-known [[Music of the Philippines#Original Pilipino music|original Pilipino music]] tracks from otherwise prominent Filipino musicians, such as "Maskara" and "Pinoy Blues" by the [[Juan de la Cruz Band]]. He approached [[Dong Abay]] and [[Radioactive Sago Project]] bassist Francis de Veyra to perform the two songs, arranged by [[Armi Millare]]. Additional tracks were performed by [[Ely Buendia]], the late [[FrancisM]], and the local band Bent Lynchpin. One member of Bent Lynchpin, Fred Sandoval, was also the film's music editor.<ref name="erwin" />

According to Romulo, the tracks are "local [[hip hop music|hip hop]]" heavily influenced by [[DJ Shadow]]'s album ''[[Endtroducing.....]]''. He also credited [[film score]]s composed by [[Lalo Schifrin]], and director [[Ishmael Bernal]]'s longtime composer Vanishing Tribe as major influences for the soundtrack.<ref name="erwin" />

== Release ==
=== Theatrical run and distribution ===
''On the Job'' had its world premiere in the [[Directors' Fortnight]] section of the [[2013 Cannes Film Festival]] on May 24.<ref name="Variety review" /> Although it did not win the [[Caméra d'Or]] prize, it was well regarded by the viewers, receiving a two-minute standing ovation.<ref name="Budget" /><ref name="league">{{cite news|last1=Policarpio|first1=Alan|title=Gerald Anderson in a different league of acting|url=http://entertainment.inquirer.net/109817/gerald-anderson-in-a-different-league-of-acting|accessdate=August 17, 2017|newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|date=August 27, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130827164305/http://entertainment.inquirer.net/109817/gerald-anderson-in-a-different-league-of-acting |archivedate=August 27, 2013 |deadurl=no}}</ref> The film had its Philippine release on August 28, 2013 and, over three weeks, grossed {{Philippine peso|13,459,037}} at the box office.<ref name="Budget" /><ref name="bomPH" />

The film was released in North America on September 27 by Well Go USA Entertainment.<ref name="prodnotes">{{cite web |url=http://www.wellgousa.com/download/file/fid/1241 |publisher=Well Go USA Entertainment |title=''On the Job'' Production Notes |accessdate=May 25, 2017 |format=DOC |pages=1–3 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131006064653/http://www.wellgousa.com/download/file/fid/1241 |archivedate=2013-10-06 |df= }}</ref> Well Go USA had bought the North American rights for the film before it premiered at Cannes; they also acquired rights for [[DVD]], [[Blu-ray]], and [[video on demand]] distributions.<ref name="Deals" /><ref name="Indiewire">{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/well-go-usa-acquires-filipino-thriller-on-the-job-fresh-off-of-cannes-premiere|title=Well Go USA Acquires Filipino Thriller ''On The Job'' Ahead of Its Cannes Premiere|last=Holloway|first=Clint|date=May 24, 2013|publisher=[[IndieWire]]|accessdate=August 15, 2013|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130811041044/http://www.indiewire.com/article/well-go-usa-acquires-filipino-thriller-on-the-job-fresh-off-of-cannes-premiere|archivedate=August 11, 2013|df=}}</ref> The deal was brokered by Well Go USA President Doris Pfardrescher and [[XYZ Films]] founders Nate Bolotin and Aram Tertzakian.<ref name="Deadline">{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/05/cannes-well-go-usa-lands-n-a-rights-to-on-the-job/ |title=Cannes: Well Go USA Lands N.A. Rights To ''On The Job'' |publisher=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=May 23, 2013 |accessdate=August 15, 2013 |last=Fleming |first=Mike Jr. |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002045804/http://www.deadline.com/2013/05/cannes-well-go-usa-lands-n-a-rights-to-on-the-job/ |archivedate=October 2, 2013 |df= }}</ref> ''On the Job'' played in twenty-nine North American theaters in three weeks, grossing $164,620.<ref name="bomUS">{{cite web|title=''On the Job'' |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=onthejob.htm |publisher=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=May 23, 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170311204831/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=onthejob.htm |archivedate=March 11, 2017 |df= }}</ref> It was also released in France by Wild Side Films<ref name="Deals">{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.inquirer.net/97171/p12-m-foreign-deals-for-phs-on-the-job |title=P12-M foreign deals for PH’s ''On the Job'' |newspaper=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=June 6, 2013 |accessdate=August 15, 2013 |last=San Diego |first=Bayani Jr. |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927021545/http://entertainment.inquirer.net/97171/p12-m-foreign-deals-for-phs-on-the-job |archivedate=September 27, 2013 |df= }}</ref> and in Australia by [[Madman Entertainment]].<ref>{{cite web|title=XYZ confirms ''On the Job'' remake |url=http://www.reality.com.ph/xyz-confirms-on-the-job-remake/ |publisher=[[Reality Entertainment]] |accessdate=May 26, 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004171415/http://www.reality.com.ph/xyz-confirms-on-the-job-remake/ |archivedate=October 4, 2013 |df= }}</ref> The deals with French and North American distribution companies secured $350,000 ({{Philippine peso|12 million}}).<ref name="Deals" />

The film was also made available to the North American market through [[Netflix]] by Well Go USA.<ref>{{cite news|last1=San Diego|first1=Bayani Jr.|title=Netflix lands ‘Birdshot’|url=http://entertainment.inquirer.net/267488/netflix-lands-birdshot|accessdate=6 April 2018|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=27 March 2019}}</ref>

=== Home media ===
''On the Job'' was released on DVD and Blu-ray on February 18, 2014, courtesy of Well Go USA.<ref>{{cite web|title=On the Job (2013): Releases |url=http://www.allmovie.com/movie/on-the-job-v582887/releases |publisher=[[AllMovie]]|accessdate=February 22, 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222195328/http://www.allmovie.com/movie/on-the-job-v582887/releases |archivedate=22 February 2017 |df= }}</ref> Special features include [[making-of]] footage, [[deleted scene]]s, and film trailers of ''[[Special ID]]'', ''[[Confession of Murder]]'', and ''[[Commitment (film)|Commitment]]''. Justin Remer of [[DVD Talk]] praised both the Blu-ray's video and audio transfers while generally criticizing its special features.<ref name="dvdtalk">{{cite news|last1=Remer |first1=Justin |title=On the Job (Blu-ray) |url=http://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/62784/on-the-job/ |accessdate=June 20, 2017 |publisher=[[DVD Talk]] |date=February 12, 2014 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150921125101/http://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/62784/on-the-job/ |archivedate=September 21, 2015 }}</ref> Both Kevin Yeoman of ''High-Def Digest'' and Jeffrey Kauffman of ''Blu-ray.com'' scored the release 3.5/5, and offered similar commentary in regard to the transfers and special features.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Yeoman |first1=Kevin |title=On the Job |url=http://bluray.highdefdigest.com/10525/onthejob.html |accessdate=June 20, 2017 |publisher=High-Def Digest|date=February 18, 2014 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150508162447/http://bluray.highdefdigest.com/10525/onthejob.html |archivedate=May 8, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Kauffman |first1=Jeffrey |title=On the Job Blu-ray |url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/On-the-Job-Blu-ray/87163/#Review |accessdate=June 20, 2017 |publisher=Blu-ray.com |date=February 11, 2014 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161021123626/http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/On-the-Job-Blu-ray/87163/ |archivedate=October 21, 2016 }}</ref> ''On the Job'' accumulated $167,128 video sales in North America.<ref>{{cite web|title=On The Job (2013)|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/On-The-Job#tab=video-sales|publisher=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|accessdate=August 25, 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170825143740/http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/On-The-Job#tab=video-sales|archivedate=August 25, 2017|df=}}</ref>

== Reception ==
=== Reviews ===
''On the Job'' drew very positive reviews from both local and international critics,<ref name="rave" /> many of whom favorably compared it to the works of filmmakers [[Johnnie To]] and [[Michael Mann]].{{refn|<ref name="gmareview" /><ref name="indiewire" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Marsh|first1=James|title=Review: On the Job, Dark, Hellish And Brilliant|url=http://screenanarchy.com/2013/09/review-on-the-job-dark-hellish-and-brilliant.html|accessdate=July 4, 2017|publisher=[[Screen Anarchy]]|date=September 26, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731102136/http://screenanarchy.com/2013/09/review-on-the-job-dark-hellish-and-brilliant.html|archivedate=July 31, 2017|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref>}} The review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the film a 100% rating based on thirteen reviews, and an [[average rating]] of 6.7/10.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/on_the_job |title=''On The Job'' (2013) |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=October 29, 2014 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141030081936/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/on_the_job/ |archivedate=October 30, 2014 |df= }}</ref> [[Metacritic]] rated it 70/100 based on eleven reviews, indicating "generally favorable reviews."<ref>{{cite web |title=''On the Job'' (2013) |url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/on-the-job |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=May 25, 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005234822/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/on-the-job |archivedate=October 5, 2013 |df= }}</ref>

Justin Chang of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called it "a gritty, convoluted but steadily engrossing crime thriller ... a tense, well-acted [[B movie]]". Furthermore, he praised its soundtrack, "neon-smeared" cinematography, and "whiplash editing".<ref name="Variety review">{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2013/film/reviews/film-review-on-the-job-1200496398/ |title=Film Review: ''On the Job'' |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=June 12, 2013 |accessdate=August 16, 2013 |last=Chang |first=Justin |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130815205108/http://variety.com/2013/film/reviews/film-review-on-the-job-1200496398/ |archivedate=August 15, 2013 |df= }}</ref> Neil Young of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' described it as a "likably rough-edged hitmen-vs.-cops thriller", and similarly praised the editing and cinematography.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/job-cannes-review-560650 |title=''On the Job'': Cannes Review |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=May 30, 2013 |accessdate=August 16, 2013 |last=Young |first=Neil |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130818113503/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/job-cannes-review-560650 |archivedate=August 18, 2013 |df= }}</ref> Writing for ''[[The New York Times]]'', Jeannette Catsoulis selected ''On the Job'' as her "Critic's Pick", calling it a "propulsive thriller" which "is never less than arresting".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Catsoulis |first1=Jeannette |title=Both Sides of a Crime, Each Imperfect |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/27/movies/on-the-job-directed-by-erik-matti.html |accessdate=May 25, 2017 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 26, 2013 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706231607/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/27/movies/on-the-job-directed-by-erik-matti.html |archivedate=July 6, 2015 |df= }}</ref> Gabe Toro of [[IndieWire]] gave the film a B minus grade rating and called it "a propulsive new actioner", comparing it to the Hong Kong film ''[[Infernal Affairs]]'' (2002) and its American [[remake]] ''[[The Departed]]'' (2006).<ref name="indiewire">{{cite news|last1=Toro |first1=Gabe |title=Review: Filipino Thriller ''On The Job'' A Familiar But Exciting Echo Of ''The Departed'' |url=http://www.indiewire.com/2013/09/review-filipino-thriller-on-the-job-a-familiar-but-exciting-echo-of-the-departed-93183/ |accessdate=May 25, 2017 |publisher=IndieWire |date=September 27, 2013 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160811051230/http://www.indiewire.com/2013/09/review-filipino-thriller-on-the-job-a-familiar-but-exciting-echo-of-the-departed-93183/ |archivedate=August 11, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Justin Monroe of ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' magazine gave it 7/10, writing, "''On the Job'' could have been a simple-minded, serviceable action flick if all it had going for it was the grit and grime of Filipino streets, stylized violence, and its insane premise, but Matti's thriller has more substance, driven by more fully realized characters and the compelling relationships between these men as they struggle to survive."<ref>{{cite news|last1=Monroe |first1=Justin |title=Fantastic Fest Review: ''On the Job'' Shoots True with Inmates Freed to Carry Out Contract Killings |url=http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2013/09/on-the-job-movie-review |accessdate=May 26, 2017 |work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |date=September 25, 2013 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140113182216/http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2013/09/on-the-job-movie-review |archivedate=January 13, 2014 |df= }}</ref>

In an otherwise positive review, Allan Hunter of [[Screendaily.com]] felt the film lacked "nuanced characters or subtle dialogue", but said that nonetheless, the film was "involving enough to forgive any infelicities". He also praised the acting and subject matter, prompting him to regard it as "essential viewing on its home territory".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screendaily.com/reviews/the-latest/on-the-job/5056737.article?blocktitle=DIRECTORS%27-FORTNIGHT&contentID=40446 |title=''On The Job'' |publisher=[[Screendaily.com]] |date=May 23, 2013 |accessdate=August 16, 2013 |last=Hunter |first=Allan |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141029102237/http://www.screendaily.com/reviews/the-latest/on-the-job/5056737.article?blocktitle=DIRECTORS%27-FORTNIGHT&contentID=40446 |archivedate=October 29, 2014 |df= }}</ref> [[Derek Elley]] of ''[[Film Business Asia]]'' found the film engrossing but unnecessarily complicated at times, writing, "What keeps the viewer hooked are the performances."<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.filmbiz.asia/reviews/on-the-job |title=On the Job |work=[[Film Business Asia]] |date=May 29, 2013 |accessdate=August 16, 2013 |last=Elley |first=Derek |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130629090833/http://www.filmbiz.asia/reviews/on-the-job |archivedate=June 29, 2013 |df= }}</ref> Ignatiy Vishnevetsky of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' gave the film a B minus grade, complimenting it as "a scuzzy Filipino crime flick" that was weakened by "humdrum and occasionally heavy-handed police procedural".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vishnevetsky |first1=Ignatiy |title=''On The Job'' |url=http://www.avclub.com/review/on-the-job-103340 |accessdate=May 25, 2017 |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |publisher=The Onion, Inc. |date=September 26, 2013 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141030105824/http://www.avclub.com/review/on-the-job-103340 |archivedate=October 30, 2014 |df= }}</ref> Andrew Schenker of ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' scored the film 2.5/4, saying, "Even as the plot takes on increasingly convoluted turns, the movie never fails to keep insisting upon the rottenness of every facet of Filipino society ... [it] is far more successful when plunging us into one of its thrilling action set pieces."<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schenker |first1=Andrew |title=''On the Job'' |url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/on-the-job |accessdate=May 25, 2017 |work=[[Slant Magazine]] |date=September 23, 2013 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907024051/http://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/on-the-job |archivedate=September 7, 2015 |df= }}</ref>

In the Philippines, members of the [[Cinema Evaluation Board]] gave the film a grade of "A."<ref name="pepreview" /> Mikhail Lecaros of [[GMA News]] praised the action scenes as "technically polished while simultaneously visceral {{en dash}} even intimate {{en dash}} in their brutality".<ref name="gmareview">{{cite news|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/324329/lifestyle/reviews/movie-review-on-the-job-is-a-two-fisted-tale-of-scum-and-villainy |title=Movie review: ''On the Job'' is a two-fisted tale of scum and villainy |last=Lecaros |first=Mikhail |publisher=[[GMA News]] |date=August 30, 2013 |accessdate=October 29, 2014 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141029110456/http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/324329/lifestyle/reviews/movie-review-on-the-job-is-a-two-fisted-tale-of-scum-and-villainy |archivedate=October 29, 2014 |df= }}</ref> Writing for [[Rappler]], Carljoe Javier expressed hope that the film would "[serve] as a shot of adrenaline, not only to the hearts of viewers, but hopefully also to mainstream cinema".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Javier |first1=Carljoe |title=''On the Job'': Adrenaline shot |url=http://www.rappler.com/entertainment/movies/38304-on-the-job-adrenaline-shot |accessdate=May 25, 2017 |publisher=[[Rappler]] |date=September 7, 2013 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130911073002/http://www.rappler.com/entertainment/movies/38304-on-the-job-adrenaline-shot |archivedate=September 11, 2013 |df= }}</ref> Mari-An Santos of [[Philippine Entertainment Portal]] highly recommended it as "a well-crafted film, from script to direction and acting to post-production ... it's a damn good film".<ref name="pepreview">{{cite news|last1=Santos |first1=Mari-An |title=Movie Review: ''OTJ'' (''On The Job'') |url=http://www.pep.ph/guide/movies/12460/movie-review-otj-on-the-job |accessdate=May 25, 2017 |publisher=Philippine Entertainment Portal |date=August 30, 2013 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130902024306/http://www.pep.ph/guide/movies/12460/movie-review-otj-on-the-job |archivedate=September 2, 2013 |df= }}</ref> Phillip Cu-Unjieng of ''[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]'' praised the ensemble cast as "top-notch" and the film as "dark, brooding, muscular and visceral, yet complex and concise in its story-telling".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cu-Unjieng |first1=Phillip |title=Film review: ''On The Job'': It's 'bitter' in the Philippines |url=http://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2013/08/29/1145601/film-review-job-its-bitter-philippines |accessdate=May 26, 2017 |newspaper=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=August 29, 2013 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921044822/http://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2013/08/29/1145601/film-review-job-its-bitter-philippines |archivedate=September 21, 2013 |df= }}</ref>

=== Accolades ===
In addition to featuring at the Cannes Film Festival, ''On the Job'' was screened at the 17th [[Puchon International Fantastic Film Festival]] in [[Bucheon]], [[South Korea]].<ref name="sokor">{{cite news|last1=San Diego, Jr. |first1=Bayani |title=''On the Job'', Joel Torre win in Korea |url=http://entertainment.inquirer.net/105349/on-the-job-joel-torre-win-in-korea |accessdate=June 29, 2017 |newspaper=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=July 28, 2013 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130823021349/http://entertainment.inquirer.net/105349/on-the-job-joel-torre-win-in-korea |archivedate=August 23, 2013 }}</ref> Joel Torre won the Best Actor award and the film received the Jury Prize.<ref name="sokor" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/guide/movies/12295/joel-torre-wins-best-actor-otj-on-the-job-wins-jury-prize-in-south-korea |title=Joel Torre wins Best Actor, OTJ (On the Job) wins Jury prize in South Korea |publisher=Philippine Entertainment Portal |date=July 28, 2013 |accessdate=August 16, 2013 |last=Dimaculangan |first=Jocelyn |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130818064502/http://www.pep.ph/guide/movies/12295/joel-torre-wins-best-actor-otj-on-the-job-wins-jury-prize-in-south-korea |archivedate=August 18, 2013 |df= }}</ref> At the [[2014 FAMAS Awards|62nd FAMAS Awards]], the film won six of its twelve nominations{{em dash}}[[FAMAS Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[FAMAS Award for Best Director|Best Director]] (Matti), Best Screenplay (Matti and Michiko Yamamoto), Best Editing (Jay Halili), Best Story (Matti), and Best Sound (Corinne de San Jose). [[Piolo Pascual]] also received the [[Fernando Poe Jr. Memorial Award for Excellence]] for his performance.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dimaculangan|first1=Jocelyn|title=KC Concepcion and ER Ejercito win top acting honors in 62nd FAMAS Awards|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/showbiz/pep/370102/kc-concepcion-and-er-ejercito-win-top-acting-honors-in-62nd-famas-awards/story/|accessdate=July 29, 2017|publisher=GMA News |date=July 14, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731102141/http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/showbiz/pep/370102/kc-concepcion-and-er-ejercito-win-top-acting-honors-in-62nd-famas-awards/story/|archivedate=July 31, 2017|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref> At the [[37th Gawad Urian Awards]], the film received eight nominations, winning two{{em dash}}[[Gawad Urian for Best Actor|Best Actor]] (Torre), and Best Sound (de San Jose).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Reyes|first1=William|title=30th PMPC Star Awards for Movies nominees unveiled|url=http://www.pep.ph/guide/movies/13459/30th-pmpc-star-awards-for-movies-nominees-unveiled|accessdate=July 29, 2017|publisher=Philippine Entertainment Portal|date=February 24, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305090133/http://www.pep.ph/guide/movies/13459/30th-pmpc-star-awards-for-movies-nominees-unveiled|archivedate=March 5, 2016|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Villano|first1=Alexa|title=Full List: Winners at the 37th Gawad Urian Awards|url=http://www.rappler.com/entertainment/news/60909-full-list-winners-gawad-urian-awards-2014|accessdate=July 29, 2017|publisher=Rappler|date=June 18, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150128033251/http://www.rappler.com/entertainment/news/60909-full-list-winners-gawad-urian-awards-2014|archivedate=January 28, 2015|df=}}</ref>

