{{further|Holocaust victims}}
Most historians define the Holocaust as the German genocide of the European Jews, carried out between 1941 and 1945.{{efn|name=definition}} Donald Niewyk and Francis Nicosia, writing in ''The Columbia Guide to the Holocaust'' (2000), favour a definition that focuses on the Jews, [[Romani genocide|Roma]] and handicapped ([[Aktion T4]] victims), because they were targets of Nazi efforts to destroy entire groups based on heredity.{{sfn|Niewyk|Nicosia|2000|p=52}}

The broadest definition of the Holocaust would include ethnic Poles, Soviet citizens, Soviet prisoners of war, gay men, and political opponents, and would raise the death toll to 17&nbsp;million.{{sfn|Niewyk|Nicosia|2000|p=45}} A research project started in 2000, led by [[Geoffrey Megargee]] and [[Martin C. Dean|Martin Dean]] for the [[United States Holocaust Memorial Museum]], estimated in 2013 that 15–20 million people had died or been imprisoned in the sites they have identified to date.{{sfn|Lichtblau|2013}}

